# Node.js + MongoDB

This project uses the official `mongodb` driver (not Mongoose) against the Atlas `sample_mflix` database.

## Connection pattern

- Reuse the cached client in `src/lib/mongodb.ts` via `global._mongoClientPromise`.
- Read `MONGODB_URI` and database/collection names from `src/lib/env.ts` — never hardcode credentials.
- Export `getDb()` for collection access; do not create a new `MongoClient` per request.

## Query modules

- Keep query logic in `src/lib/movies.ts` (or similar lib modules), not in React components.
- Type collections with document interfaces from `src/types/movie.ts`.
- Serialize MongoDB documents before passing to UI: convert `ObjectId` to string, normalize optional fields, and apply helpers like `normalizeYear`.

## Query safety

- Escape user input used in `$regex` filters (`escapeRegex` in `src/lib/regex.ts`).
- Return empty results or safe defaults for blank search queries instead of throwing.
- Use typed `Filter<Document>` from `mongodb` for query builders.

## Error handling

- Catch connection and query errors at the page or caller boundary.
- Surface `Error.message` to the UI when appropriate; log details server-side only.
- Do not leak connection strings or raw driver errors to the client.

## Performance

- Use `.limit()`, `.sort()`, and projection when listing or searching movies.
- Prefer indexed fields (`title`, `year`, `imdb.rating`) for filters and sorts.
- Avoid loading unbounded result sets.

## Testing

- Unit-test pure helpers (`buildTitleSearchFilter`, `normalizeYear`, `escapeRegex`) without a live database.
- Mock `getDb` when testing modules that hit MongoDB.
